Facebooks codebase changes each day as engineers develop and optimize our apps, and each of those changes goes through automated regression tests before deployment. But how do we test the tests? Facebook Engineering developed a way to measure test flakiness, the Probabilistic Flakiness Score. Learn how PFS came to be and how its used to ensure quality code: https://fb.me/Facebook-PFS

The probabilistic flakiness score helps us measure and monitor test reliability and quickly adapt to any changes over time.
engineering.fb.com

Facebook for Developers
December 16, 2020

Developers of ML models have a responsibility to preserve data privacy from hackers and other unauthorized parties. Facebook AI and OpenMined have partnered up to offer developers a series of courses to teach awareness, privacy foundations, cross-enterprise statistics, and federated statistics and learning. The Private AI Series is based on PyTorch and the awareness course begins in January 2021. Learn more about the series: https://fb.me/Facebook-AI-OpenMined

You can also register for the courses here: https://fb.me/Facebook-AI-OpenMined-Join

Oculus Developers believe that the magic of VR shouldnt be limited to those with diverse audio, visual, movement, or other accessibility requirements. To show their commitment to this idea, theyve recently introduced new Accessibility Virtual Reality Checks focused on ensuring that VR experiences are open to all. Learn more about these recommended tech specs, and find other resources for inclusive design: https://fb.me/Introducing-the-Accessibility-VRCs

As we focus on making the future of VR human, it's imperative that the wonderful new worlds and realities that you are building can be enjoyed by everyone.

When Pinterest learned Android users wanted a smoother login process, the company needed to find a way to implement a seamless experience that did not require them to re-select a login method or re-enter login credentials. By integrating Express Login and Custom Tab for Android, a Facebook Login tool, Pinterest saw a nearly 40% increase in conversions for logging in from Android users. Learn more about their insights and results here: https://fb.me/Success-Story-pinterest

The Facebook Engineering team wanted to make the data discovery process fast and ensure that the information was accurate to make informed decisions and take proper action. To do so, they built Nemo, an internal data discovery engine that has improved search success rates by more than 50%, reduced the time spent looking for data, increased data usage quality, and more. See why Nemo gives engineers high confidence in finding the right data: https://fb.me/Nemo-Facebook-Data-Discovery
